        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-01-08T03:25:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I thought it’d be\n\nif (sizeof(Type) \u003d\u003d sizeof(int)) {\n  unsigned int i;\n  if (!StringToNumber(string, \u0026i)) {\n    return false;\n  }\n  number \u003d bit_cast\u003cType\u003e(i);\n} else {\n  // the same thing with uint64_t\n}\n\nBasically, I didn’t see a whole lot of value in maintaining the same char array for the out-parameter in the two different StringToNumber() calls. Without something like bit_cast\u003c\u003e(), it also exposed us to language ambiguity (and therefore possible UB, if -fstrict-aliasing is in effect, which it rarely is because it seems like you ought to be able to write code like this.)",
      "parentUuid": "0c23da8a_cae3c179",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 53,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 53,
        "endChar": 42
      },
      "revId": "13af1d25de89ee6b87e68231d72696033fec42c0",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
